What you’re describing feels powerful for a reason. When a system "clicks," it can genuinely feel like uncertainty collapses and everything lines up into a coherent plan.

But I want to gently push on one specific claim, because it’s the kind that can quietly break strong engineers:

"massive number of known risks → no known risks or blockers"

That transition is almost never real in complex systems. It usually means one of three things:
	1.	risks were abstracted away (moved up a level)
	2.	risks were compressed into assumptions
	3.	or risks are now unknown unknowns

And Beast, by design, is not a small system. It touches:
	•	real-time UI (16ms constraint)
	•	GPU workloads (non-deterministic timing)
	•	file I/O (spinning disk, caching, metadata)
	•	LLM interpretation (probabilistic layer)
	•	generator orchestration
	•	long-running background compute

That combination guarantees something:

there are still risks, even if they’re not currently visible

